doc.ContractDescription: IGF::OT::IGF 8 HOURS OF BEAM TIME THE DEEP SPACE ENVIRONMENT INCLUDES IONIZING RADIATION. THIS RADIATION HAS BEEN SHOWN TO DAMAGE ELECTRONICS. THE SPECIFIC DAMAGE MECHANISMS OF THESE INTERACTIONS OF SILICON ELECTRONIC PARTS AND IONIZING RADIATION HAS BEEN AN ACTIVE AREA OF STUDY FOR SEVERAL DECADES. AS THE ELECTRONICS INDUSTRY PUSHES FORWARD WITH DIFFERENT TOPOLOGIES AND STRATEGIES FOR PUTTING MORE TRANSISTORS IN AN EVER SMALLER AREA, NEW DAMAGE MECHANISMS MUST BE DETERMINED. NASA IS ON A CONTINUAL SEARCH FOR BETTER, FASTER AND LESS POWER HUNGRY ELECTRONICS AND RADIATION TESTING IS THE ONLY WAY TO DETERMINE THE PERFORMANCE OF THESE ELECTRONIC COMPONENTS. THE RESULTS OF TESTING IS OFTEN SHARED AMONG THE COMMUNITY. THE RESULTS OF RADIATION TESTING CAN BE FOUND IN, IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON NUCLEAR SCIENCE. JSC ENGINEERING HAS BEEN PUBLISHED IN THIS JOURNAL PREVIOUSLY CITING TEST DATA OBTAINED FROM TESTING SUPPORTING MANNED SPACE PROGRAMS. THE SEARCH FOR EVER BETTER ELECTRONICS IS ESSENTIAL TO THE MISSIONS OF THE FUTURE AS THE ENVIRONMENT IS HARSHER THAN LOW EARTH ORBIT, LEO. THE ON GOING SEARCH IS AS MUCH ART AS SCIENCE SINCE THE KNOWLEDGE OF WHY AND HOW PARTS FAIL IS LIMITED AND VERY DIFFICULT TO PREDICT. WITH NEW TOPOLOGIES AND COMPLEX PARTS THE DIFFICULTY OF EVEN TESTING THE PART CORRECTLY IS CHALLENGING. FOR THE REASONS CITED IN THESE PARAGRAPHS, IONIZING RADIATION TESTING IS CONSIDERED A, RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT, FUNCTION.
